Comment: Also shpes(ë), shpezë.< *su-petno-t- (Huld, 1984: 154, in Kortlandt 1987).Alternatively, to pendë 'feather' < Lat. pinna, penna 'id.'. (Orel 429).

Late derivative of ftoh ~ ftof 'to cool, to make cold' < Pr. Alb. *wi-tāja, whose second element compares with Slav. *tajo, *tajati 'to melt', < PIE *teh₂- 'thaw, melt', here with suffix -f- < -h- < *-sk̑e-. The oppositive meaning derives from the preverb f- < *wi- < *apu- (Schumacher & Matzinger: 974).
Borrowed from Lat venire. Aorist continues PAlb *erdza which is etymologically identical to Gk ερχομαι 'to come'.
Orel gives nëmëroj 'to number, to count'. Loan < Lat numerāre 'id'.
vdek = infin. Orel and Dyen claim Albanian-internal cognacy only. Holm offers < *dhguhei- 'to pass away, die'. cf. also Att Gk φθι-νω 'to die'.
Relatively late loanword from Lat canem or, rather, from its Balkan continuations, reflected in the lack of rhotacism in Tosk.
Also 'to suck'. piva (aor); pirë (participle). related to IE *po(i)- 'to drink'.
Related to IE *ous-, cf also Lat auris, Lith ausis, Latv auss.
(aor. stem reflects a different root PIE *gʷerh₃- + preverb *an-)
< IE *eh3uiom, cf. Arm jvoj (gen.) and Cze vejce. Orel, however, claims it to be a loan from Latin. Both have same etymological origin, however.
From IE *h3(e)kuih1 > PALb *atsiwi, a form of dual related to - inter alia - Skt aksi, Lith akì.

From PAlb *be(r)ja derived from IE *bher- 'to strike, to beat'. Aorist form rashë goes back to PAlb *rausa, a sigmatic aorist of IE *reu- 'to tear', cf also Skt ravate 'to smash', Lat ruo 'to tear', etc. (ra, ran = INF.)
Borrowed < Lat pinna, penna 'feather; pair of oxen'. Second meaning is a metaphoric derivative of the latter, meaning more 'plumage'.
< IE *gheres, cf. Skt haras 'flame, heat'. Etymologically identical also with Gk θερμος, Arm jerm.
< Rom *fluctulare, a modification of Lat fluctuare 'to move in waves, to move to and fro'.
kâmë ~ kâmbë Loan < Romance *camba ~ *gamba (but not attested in Balkan Romance) < (Vul)Lat gamba 'leg, ankle, pastern' (itself < Grk. κάμπη)

Inf = dhan. < PAlb *en-apa with filling hiatus, or from analogy with jam. Orel states this form to be parallel to IE *ap-/*ep- although Holm strongly disputes this. He claims no IE cognates outside Alb. Aor = dhase.
A singularised neut. plural PAlb *dara < IE *ghesr-, related to Gk χεîρ, Hitt. keššar, Toch A tsar-, Toch B sar-, Arm jern, all with identical meanings.
Together wirh Gr. κρᾱνίον, Ved. śīrṣṇá- going back to PIE *k̑roh₂sno- 'head'.
< Lat. intelligere 'to perceive'. More evident in dialect forms, such as this one (ndëgoj), Çamic endiglo and Old Geg (Buzuku) ëndiglonj.
Also 'middle'. A difficult word without any reliable explanation.
gjuej besides (esp. older) gjuo(n)j and contracted gjuj.
From PAlb *awa-rautja, a prefix derivative based on IE *reu 'to tear, destroy': Skt rutá- 'broken', Lat ruo 'to fall down, to rush down' etc. INF = vra.
From PAlb *dija connected with IE *dhei(ə)- 'to see', cf Skt dhyā(ya)ti 'to observe, feel, think', Av dā(y)- 'to see'. INF = dit.
From PAlb *gadza. Etymologically connected with OHG questa 'tuft', PN kvistr 'branch'. Slav *gvozdb 'wood, forest'.
Borrowed < Rom *manctus, based on Lat mancus 'maimed, infirm', cf also Ital manca 'left hand'.
Also 'foot'. Borrowed < Rom *camba ~ *gamba 'leg, although direction of borrowing may be uncertain.

'live, stay'; < Pr. Alb. *rānja-, which is connected by Orel with Lith. róju, róti 'to cope, be ready', thus pointing to a root PIE **reh₁i̯-, but connected with Alb, rri 'sit, stay' it could go back to *(h₁)rei̯d- 'lean', LIV 503, Matzinger & Schumacher 994, with different stem formation and preverb *an-.

Borrowed < Ital milza id., possibly even earlier < Goth *milti (cf Cat melsa) 'milt, spleen'. Suppletion zeze 'black' follows Trk usage of colours for entrails, cf karaciger 'liver' with kara 'black'.
From PAlb *dlata continuing IE *dlngh-to- and related to other IE adjectives for 'long'.
From PAlb *mērwa based on IE *mer- 'to die' as Gk φθειρ is based on φθειρω 'to destroy'. Holm claims this is hardly likely and prefers the IE origin *merh2- 'to squeeze' via PAlb mēr(e)n.
From PAlb *miša further related to IE *memso-, cf also - inter alia - Skt māmsa-, Arm mis, Goth mimz, Slav *męso.
Identical with Lith. malà and Latv. mala 'bank, shore '. Also *mal- is reflected in ancient Balkan toponymy.
Borrowed < It gola id (?), made obvious by variant golë.
From PAlb *enmen- or *inmen-, etymologically close to OIr ainm, Slav *jbmę, PRus emnes, all meaning the same, and to other continuations of IE *(o)noHmn.
Borrowed < Turk. kafa 'occupit, head'. Poss. link with Lat. caput? Rum ceafă is an Albanian loanword!
Also 'young, recent'. From PAlb *rija < IE *er-, *or- 'to rise, to make move', cf ON orr 'quick', OS aru id, of similar origin.
From PAlb *nakti- corresponding to IE *nokut- > Skt nákt, Gk νυξ, Lat nox, etc, all with same meaning.
Goes back to PAlb *skun-tā derived from *skuna> hu.
From IE *sem- via Balkan-IE *sm-ijos > Arm mi, Gk μια and PAlb *mja. Orel disagrees, postulating an IE origin of *oi-no > Lat ūnus, Goth and OPrus ains, etc, all with identical meanings.
From PAlb *sūja, also connected with IE *sū- 'rain; to rain' and OPrus suge 'rain'.
Also 'oak'. From PAlb *wradnjā etymologically connected with Gk ραδιξ 'branch', Lat radix, Welsh gwraidd etc., all with same meaning.
Borrowed < Lat arēna id. Holm, however, prefers an alternative etymology < IE *er- 'sand, locker' (cf Lat rārus) but has no recent cognates.
From PAlb *sāksa, further connected to IE *seku- 'to follow, to see', Skt sácate 'to accompany, to follow', Gk επομαι, Lat sequor; also notably Goth saihvan 'to see'.
Adjectival derivative of of pref ~ preh < *për-eh with eh < Pr. Alb. *a(k)ska-, a *-ske/o- formation to PIE *h₂ek̑- 'sharp'.
Borrowed < Gmc *skurtaz 'short': OHG scurz, OE sceort 'id'.
Also 'to stand, to stay, to remain'. Goes back to PAlb *rina etymologically xlose to Skt rnóti 'to arise, to move', Gk ορνυμαι 'to move up' and related forms. See also [lexeme 929](lex-929).
Also 'hide, bark'. From PAlb *lauk-ura derived from IE *leuk- 'to shine, to be white''. Holm disagrees, proposing a form comprising the prefix lë- + kur = loan < Lat corium 'thick skin, leather'.
From PAlb *awa-leja, etymologically connected with Slav. *lĕjo, *lĕjati 'to doze, slumber'. Contested by Holm.

From PAlb *wāgla, *wāgra related to Lat vagor 'to roam around', OIr fán 'slope' < *uāg-no-. Originates semantically from 'to be crooked'. Holm, however, proposes a borrowing from Trk ufaklik 'tinyness' (< Arab faqīr 'poor').
Continues PAlb *ātuma connected with Gmc *ēdumaz 'breath' and further related to Skt ātmán- 'blow, breath, soul'. Holm argues it is a loan < Gk θνμος from IE *dhueh2-.
Also 'to sit, to stay, to remain'. Goes back to PAlb *rina etymologically close to Skt rnóti 'to arise, to move', Gk ορνυμαι 'to move up' and related forms. See also [lexeme 916](lex-916).
Goes back to PAlb *skīw-ila, derived from *skijā > hije 'shadow' (Orel). Holm, however, prefers an IE origin in *h1eus 'burn, glow'.
Also 'rock'. From PAlb *gura continuing IE *guer- 'mountain', cf Skt gir-, Av gairi-, Lith girià 'wood', Latv dziria id and Slav *gora 'mountain, wood'.

Orel gives the old idea of a derivation from PIE *g̑ʰelh₃-u̯o- 'yellow', but Holm (p. 82) suggests alternatively to put it back to PIE *dei̯h₂- (LIV 108) 'blaze, shine', viz. *d(e)i̯h₂-lo-, cf. Alb. ditë 'day(light)' < *dih₂-to-.
Nasal lost secondary after the aorist; frequent in the same meaning non-active âjem.
Loan < Rom *notāre, replacing ClLat natāre, same meaning. Holm prefers notim 'swimming' < IE snéh2-timo, cf Gk νηχω id.
Alternative (so in Dyen) shtij/shtie has a more specialized meaning 'cast, shoot, project into sth.' (cf. e.g. Mann 1948 s.v.).

From PAlb *glusā, further connected with IE dial. *golso- 'sound', cf also ON kall 'shout', Lith galsas 'echo', Slav golsъ 'voice'. Holm disagrees, favouring instead a root in IE *dnghuā 'tongue', cf [cognate set 327](cog-327)(cognate class W).
From PAlb *dzamba, a dialectal IE word for tooth shared with TochA, TochB, Latv, Slav, etc. Original meaning is preserved in Gk γομφος and Skt jámbha- 'peg'.
Also 'wood'. From PAlb *druwa < PIE dru(-n) etymologically compared with Slav drъvo 'wood', Skt dru- id., Av dru- id., etc.

From PAlb *bardza continuing *bhorəgo-, a derivative of IE *bhereg- 'to shine; white', cf Skt bhrājate '(he) shines, beams, glitters', Goth bairhts 'light, shining' and the word for birch: Lith bérzas, Slv *berza.
North Eastern Geg: Kosovo;Loan < Turkish sarı 'yellow'. The Standard word verdhë denotes 'green'.
Apparently from կուռն kowṙ-n 'back' + -ակ -ak (forming diminutives from nominal stems).
Traditionally, խած- xac- is derived from *kʰad-i̯e- (cf. Ved. khādati 'chew, bite'). Cf. also խոտ xot 'grass' [cognate set 593](cog-593).
կիթ kitʿ"(act of collecting) animal product(s)", such as 'milk(ing)', 'butter', '(collecting) eggs', etc.
Suppletive past stem: ինկա- ink-a-; cf. CA անկա- ank-a- (with a later alternative form ընկա-  ənk-a-) 'id.'.
Denominative of (CA) կռիւ kṙiw 'fight, strife; uproar'.

Linked with Skt. meghá- m. 'cloud, gloomy weather', Av. maēɣa- m. 'cloud', Gr. ὀμίχλη 'mist, fog', Lith. miglà 'fog', Dutch dial. miggelen 'staubregnen', etc. Other scholars consider it a loan < Iranian.
From a Proto-Armenian compound of *mit-a- 'mind' (< PIE *mēd-es-h₂; cf. Gk. μῆδος) and *ac-e- 'drive; lead' (< PIE h₂eg̑-e/o-).
Cf. passivized այրվել ayr-v-e-l 'to burn, i.e. to be consumed by fire'.

In the Canon it is attested in prepositional phrases with the meaning 'on the left' only. However, in younger texts it is attested as a adjective 'left' too.
The lexeme is not attested in the Canon. Its meaning in later texts is slightly ambiguous ('liver' or 'guts').

It has two synonimical meanings 'narrow like a narrow river, road, table etc.' and 'narrow with a connotation of very little or too litte space, tight'. Probably the first meaning predominated but it is not entirely clear.
An alternative lexeme is 'шия' but it is much less frequent in the Canon (1 time vs 36 times).

Alternative lexemes are 'вєтъхъ' and 'дрєвь(л҄ь)н҄ь'. 'дрєвь(л҄ь)н҄ь' has is more like 'very old, ancient' or 'previous, former'. ALso 'вєтъхъ' tends to mean 'very old, ancient' (notabene, it is used in the name '*Old* Testament'.
In the Canon it seems to be attested only in the meaning 'to have fun, to entertain. However, the meaning 'to play a game' is attested in younger texts.
Alternative lexeme is 'рѣяти', historically with the same root. However, the words are attested only in a meaning 'pushing people (in crowd)'.
An alternative derivative is 'изгнилъ'. Both forms can refer to wood too.
The word is not attested in the Canon (however, the basal substantive is).

Alternative lexemes are 'повѣдѣти' and 'съказати'. 'повѣдѣти' is more like 'tell' and 'notify'; 'съказати' has expect 'say' many meanings: 'elucidate, translate, mean, remind, announce' (and 'say' seems not to be the most frequent meaning).
The infinitive and any of personal forms is not attested in OCS. There is only a participal form 'шьвенъ' attested.
The word is not attested in the Canon but in younger texts only.
An alternative lexeme is 'хѹдъ' which is, however, much less frequently attested in the Canon (>200 vs. 21).

There are quite many alternative lexemes: 'жрьдь, посоха, дрьколь, дрѫгъ, жьзлъ'. However, some of them are pretty rare attested in the Canon ('дрѫгъ' and 'посоха' appear only once). Farther, they all are attested in more specific meanings like 'club, bar, sceptre'. 'палица' seems to be the best lexeme for the Swadesh term.
There is also a derivative 'камыкъ' with the same meaning attested.
An alternative lexeme is 'плѹти', historically with the same root.
Attested twice in the Canon. An alternative lexeme 'хоботъ' is attested once. Younger texts have other alternative lexemes: 'очєсъ' and 'ошибъ'.
There was possibly a dialectal variant 'тєплъ' (-e- in attested in the Canon in derivatives).

'лѣсъ' is attested twice in the Canon. There are alternative lexemes: 'дрѧзга' (attested once as 'woods, grove, coppice'), 'дѫбрава' (attested five times as 'grove, coppice, oak woods, deciduous forest') and 'лѫгъ' (attested once as 'woods, grove, coppice').

An alternative lexeme is 'годъ'. However, it attested only once in the Canon. Both words have other original meaning which seem to be stil primary in the OCS time: 'лѣто' is 'summer', 'годъ' is 'appropriate, appointed time'.

The word 'жльтъ' is not attested in OCS. However, the derivative 'жльтѣница' 'a kind of plant with yellow flowers' and the contaminated form 'жльчь' (instead of / alongside зльчь) 'gall' show that such an adjective did exist. An alternative lexeme is 'плавъ' but it has a more specific meaning 'fair, fawn, colour of ripe cereals'.

Synchronically gerundive of /śwā-/ 'eat', hence 'meat' < *'that which can be eaten'.
The vocalism points to PIE acrostatic *h₁nḗh₃-mn̥ > PToch. *ñemə, but other cognates are consistent with a proterokinetic paradigm.

Fossilized pret. ptcp. of /oks-/ 'grow, age' (cf. Toch. B aukṣu); replaced in the verbal paradigm with okṣiññu to the innovative nonpres. stem okṣiññ-. Toch. A ktsets, cognate with Toch. B ktsaitse 'old', preserves the original meaning 'perfect, accomplished'.
Fem. säṃ (cf. Toch. B sana); otherwise suppletive stem ṣom- (e.g. masc. pl. ṣome, cf. Toch. B ṣemi).
Root /ʦkā-/, alternating with /ʦakā-/ in the preterite.
Final -e unexpected; influenced by Toch. B swese?
Cf. Toch. B śwālyai 'id.'; fossilized gerundive to śwā- 'eat' (from an apparent ablaut variant *śāwā-), hence '(hand) for eating'.
Derived from /ʦmā-/ 'grow'; replaced cognate of Toch. B witsako, itself an Iranian borrowing?
The less common sārm may have a more general term, 'that which is sown'.

Root /lmā-/, alternating with /lamā-/ in the subj. and pret. and /lʲmā-/ in the pret.; suppletive pres. /ṣm(a)-/. Pres. widely taken to be from PIE *sed- with *m of nonpres. stem, but source of latter itself disputed.
Root /wr-/. Intransitive; no transitive pres. forms attested.
Root /ṣtmā-/, alternating with /ṣtamā-/ in the subj. and pret. and /śmā-/ in the pret.; suppletive pres. /kəlʲ(a)-/.
Root /krk-/, attested only in subj. and pret.
Root /spārtwā-/, irregular pres. act. /sparcw(a)-/ beside mid. /sparcw-a-/.
Fem. we, cognate with Toch. B wi (both genders).
Ultimately cognate with PIE *u̯ód-r̥, but details unclear.
Generally derived from an n-stem derivative of PIE *gʷen- with dissimilation of *n > *l by the following nasal (see Pinault 2005, Fs Gercenberg), but many details remain unclear.
The less common karāś has the more general meaning of 'forest, woods, wilderness'. Cf. Toch. B karāś.
Phonetic labiovelar suggested by spellings such as pl. puklā, pᵤklā.
Attractive etymological connection with Hitt. idālu-, Luv. ādduwāl(i)- from PIE *h₁éd-wōl (Peyrot).
url: Toch. B pakwāre has the more specialized meaning of 'evil'.

Comment: Perfect semantic match in Hittite and Hieroglyphic Luvian ura- ‘great’ (van Windekens 1960, Melchert apud Adams 2013:128), but the phonological details are unclear. Toch. B māka (cf. Toch. A māk) means 'much, many'.
From PIE collective **h₁esh₂-ōr; see also Toch. A ysār.
Suppletive pl. āsta; pace Stalmaszczyk and Witczak (1990:40-1) and Katz (1997:72-7), āy probably not from PIE *h₂ést by a rule of *-s > *-y in monosyllables.
Probably not haplology from PT du. *pəścənë-në 'breasts' (Ringe 1996:71); archaic acc. pl. pastäṃ* (loc. pä[s]tänne) points to sg. paśce* (Adams 2013:386).
Root /ṣəns-/, pres. stem /ṣənṣ-ə-/ ~ /ṣəns-e-/. < IE *sems-, = Ice SEMJA 'to put together, unite'
Root /srəwka-/, alternating with /srawka-/ in the subjunctive; pres. stem /srəwk-e-/. Not cognate with Toch. A /wl-/; cf. Toch. A /sruk-/ 'kill'.
Root /rapa-/; nasal pres. replacement for PToch. root pres. *rəpa-, cf. Toch. A rpā-, inf. rpātsi.
Synchronically derived from krāke 'dirt, filth'. The rare sal may have a more specialized meaning 'impure'.
Root /yok-/. Possibly from Narten present of *h₁eh₂gʷʰ- (Kim 2000); generally derived from Narten present of *h₁egʷʰ-.
Exact meaning uncertain; usually occurs together with taur 'dust, ashes'.
Du. klautsane, cf. Toch. A klośäṃ.
Original initial consonant cluster preserved in Toch. A tkaṃ.

All forms made to the root /śəwa-/ except for preterite participle śeśu*, which presupposes a root /śəw-/; subj. 1sg. śū (PK NS 58 b2) may be an error for expected śuwau (Peyrot 2013:484, pace Pinault 1994b:170-82).
Du. eśane; older eś in yn-eś 'evident', eś lmau 'blinded', lit. 'sat (on) the eyes'.
Root /pərska-/, alternating with /praska-/ in the subjunctive and (exceptionally) present. Remodeled from (post-)PIE *pṛK-sḱé/ó-, cf. GERMANIC.
Root /wəyta-/, to judge from weta 'struggle' and other derivatives. Apparent subj. /wə́ta-/ in v.n. watalyñe unclear.
From *ph₂u̯ōr ← PIE collective *péh₂-u̯ōr; see also Toch. A por.
Possible very early borrowing from an IE language of eastern Europe (Balto-Slavic, Ringe 1996:92); for other connections, see Adams 2013:590.
Loss of nasal between pre-TB *i and sibilant regular here and in mīsa; see MEAT.
Etymology unknown; cf. Toch. A pyāpyi
Root /pləw-/, alternating with /plʲew-/ in the subj. and pret.
Ultimately from a derivative *pod-yo-, though the exact source of the unusual sequence -aiy- is unclear; the unextended noun survives in -pew '-footed' < PIE *pod-w(e)nt- and perhaps du. paine.
Fem. kartsa, otherwise suppletive stem krent-. Originally a participle to *ĝʰer- 'find favor with' (van Windekens 1976:232), rather than *gʷerh₂- 'approve' (Pinault 1979:349).
Attested only in acc. atiyai, pl. atiyañ; usually attested in plural.
Plurale tantum; cognate with Latv. mats?
From PToch. *śəṣə́rə < PIE acc. *g̑ʰés-r-m̥ with contraction. Exact relationship with TA tsar uncertain, though most scholars derive them from the same PIE source.
Diphthong /ew/ is preserved as ew, eu in early texts.
Toch. B pl. käryāñ (IOL Toch 1 a4) continues PIE *k̂erd-, cf. Toch. A kri 'will'.
Cf. Toch. A kärn- 'id.' Toch. B /pyak-/ has a similar but more specific meaning 'strike (down), beat (a drum)'.
Attested in acc. krorīyai; cf. Toch. A kror 'crescent'. Generally taken from the family of *k̂rh₂sn- 'horn', but Hilmarsson (1985) compares Arm. ełǰiwr < PIE *g̑ʰréh₁-u̯r̥.

Only form attested. Claimed loanword from Indo-Iranian, but just as likely inherited; denominative to śerwe 'hunter' (cf. Toch. A śaru). Latter prob. a vrddhi-derivative of PIE *k̂erwo- 'stag' (Jasanoff apud Nussbaum 1986:8), rather than **g̑ʰu̯ēr-u- (so Adams 2013:694).
Attested only in dual; extended form with productive du. ending -ne presupposed by adj. kenine-ṣṣe 'pertaining to the knees' (cf. Toch. A kanweṃ).

Root /ayk-/, pres./subj. stem /ayś-ə-/ ~ /ayk-e-/. Meaning very similar to that of /kərsa-/ (not clearly distinguished like Ger. wissen vs. kennen, Fr. savoir vs. connaître, or Pol. wiedzieć vs. znać), but rather 'know, recognize'; note Toch. B po-aiśi, poyśi 'the All-Knowing' (epithet of the Buddha).
Root /kərsa-/, alternating with /karsa-/ in the subjunctive and /śərsa-/ in the preterite.
Root /ker-/, pres. stem /kerəy-ə/e-/; attested only in 3pl. keriyeṃ, keryeṃ.
Attested only in acc. ckāckai, du. ckāckane.
Root /śay-/, pres./subj. stem /śay-ə-/ ~ /śay-e-/, with fossilized ptcp. śamāne < (pre-)Proto-Toch. *śaw-ë-manë.
Attested only in acc. pl. pärseriṃ.
Loss of nasal between pre-TB *i and sibilant regular here and in piś; see FIVE.
Toch. A ñom points to PIE acrostatic *h₁nḗh₃-mn̥ > PToch. *ñemə, but other cognates are consistent with a proterokinetic paradigm.
From y(n)- 'in' + spe 'near, next to' (analyzed as a "proximative" case ending by Winter (1998:160)).
Suppletive stem ṣem- in rest of masc. paradigm. Fem. sana, acc. somo.
Root /nətka-/, alternating with /natka-/ in the subjunctive and /ñətka-/ in the preterite. Attested pres. 3sg. natknaṃ, beside alternative pres. nättaṅkäṃ /nət-ə́n-k-ən/ to a root /nətk-/.
Early Iranian loan, cf. Ossetic (Iron) widag, (Digor) jedagæ.
Apparent pret. ptcp. of a root /ampa-/ 'rot', but possibly borrowed from Middle Iranian
Attested acc. sg. waräñc (with orthographic variation).
Root /weñ-/, weakly suppletive pres. /weṣṣ-ə-/ ~ /wesk-e-/. Cf. Toch. A tränkäṣ ≠ weñ-.
Root /ləka-/, alternating with /lʲəka-/ in the preterite. Pres. act. stem /ləka-ṣṣ-ə-/ ~ /ləka-sk-e-/, otherwise identical to subj. /ləka-/. Iptv. forms to /pəlka-/, cf. Toch. A nonpres. /plkā-/.
The less common sārm may have a more general term, 'that which is sown'.
Root /pəya-/, alternating with /paya-/ in the preterite and apparently also subjunctive (v.n. pāyalñe /páya-/). Attested piyaṃ is subj. 3pl.; the 3sg. might have been pāyaṃ*. Pres. stem unknown.

Root /ləma-/, alternating with /lama-/ in the subj. and /lʲəma-/ in the pret.; suppletive pres. /ṣəm-ə/e-/. Latter widely taken to be from PIE *sed- with *m of nonpres. stem, but source of latter itself disputed.
The less common ewe seems to have the meaning 'inner skin, dermis'.
Root /wər-/, pres. stem /wər-(ə)ṣṣ-ə-/ ~ /wər-(ə)sk-e-/. Apparently has both transitive and intransitive meanings.
The less common auk seems to mean 'serpent, dragon'; it is explicitly contrasted with arṣāklo in B503 a2.
Attested only in the derived adjective śiñcatstse.
Root /stəma-/, alternating with /stama-/ in the subj. and /ścəma-/ in the pret.; suppletive pres. /kəlʲ-ə/e-/.
Attested ścirye; i for *ä in initial syllable due to preceding palatal cluster.
Root /pəlska-/, alternating with /palska-/ in the subjunctive.
Fem. tarya < PIE neut. *trih2 (cf. Toch. A tri).
Root /səl-/, pres. morphologically causative (with problematic pret. ṣālla, mid. ṣalāte). The rare verb /kərsk-/ (pres. karṣṣäṃ*) has the meaning 'shoot (e.g. an arrow), strew'.
Root /śənm-/. The rare verb /kərk-/, pres. kärkaṣṣäṃ* seems to mean 'bind (to)', to judge from TA parallels.
From *ĝn̥dʰu̯éh₂- ← PIE *dn̥g̑ʰu̯éh₂- by metathesis of place of articulation (see Ringe 1996:45-6).

Cf. klautkäṣṣäṃ 'turns', causative pres. of /klawtka-/ 'turn, become', ultimately denominative to klautke 'turn, manner, behavior'. Etymological connection to PIE *kʷelh₁- likely but not assured, pace Adams. Toch. B /spartta-/ has the more general sense 'turn; concern, conduct o.s.', cf. spertte 'conduct, behavior'.
Originally feminine, from PIE *dwóyh₁ (cf. Tocharian A we).
Root /layka-/; nasal pres. replacement for PToch. root pres. *ləyka-, cf. Toch. A līktsi, lyīktsi.
Ultimately cognate with PIE *u̯ód-r̥, but details unclear.
Also wartse; the more common aurtse is from intensive e(n)- + wartse.
Regular from *h₂u̯ēnt-ó- < *h₂u̯eh₁-nt-ó- (cf. Lat. ventus, Goth. winds), in turn a vrddhi derivative of *h₂u̯éh₁-n̥t- (cf. Hittite ḫuwant-).
Generally derived from an n-stem derivative of PIE *gʷen- with dissimilation of *n > *l by the following nasal (see Pinault 2005, Fs Gercenberg), but many details remain unclear.
The less common karāś has the more general meaning of 'forest, jungle, wilderness'. Cf. Toch. A kārāś.
Etymology ambiguous: deverbal *pekʷ-l̥ to *pekʷ- 'cook, ripen', referring to the yearly blooming of vegetation in springtime, or perhaps *h₁pi-kʷlh₁- 'turning, cycle' to *kʷelh₁- 'turn' (Katz 1994)?

Gloss: m., Pali yakkha- m. 'supernatural being', cf. Mayrhofer KEWA III, p. 1f.

Comment: also 'stomach' (in other dialects and Standard Alb. its primary meaning)

Gloss: wing (of a bird or other creature); feather

Comment: Rather 'water' [lexeme 24005](lex-24005) (also typically used of rain when combined witht he def article)
the optional d- of deigh is prothetic from the Old Irish article ind: ind aig > an deigh
AF? BRI, BRE > cogn. with [cognate set 261](cog-261)
is the PIE Form not g(w)e/orm-?
should be the same as in eng. 'shank' but with different, more general semantics
rather used in plural Haren, (both) horns
no difference between collective, plural or singular
root ref. form is wrong. root. lang. is wrong too. should be a loan. (Lat.)
cognate with 'pull' in [cognate set 2834](cog-2834) and 'rub' in cognate set 1167
like Lett. SPICE fr. NHG SPITZE 'lace'?MHG büeʒen 'to mend (clothes)'.
intransitive. only transitive in the meaning: to play an instrument.
exists also in other NHG dialects close to Luxembourgish (pfälz. Gnast/Gnascht/Knascht, 'dirty (crust)') (rhein. Knast 'dirt (on clothes)') (loth.Knascht '(sticking) dirt')eng. nasty?
Germ. 'trocken'? origin of ʃ here unclear. Should be caused by the preceding Vowel (with Umlaut) < *droχən ? Spontaneous change *k>*χ?
An alternative lexeme is 'імгла', but it has also a meaning 'drizzle'.
Lat. saxum 'large stone, rock', It. sasso (Buck 1949: 51)

From athematic PAlb *tsānsmi, etymologically connected with Lat cēnseō 'to assess, to value' and its cognates. Holm disagrees, favouring instead the IE origin *kêHs- 'to advise' > PAlb θēm > pres. thom. (THAN = INF.)
Middle English via Anglo-Norman rounde, variant of Old French rond, ultimately from vulgar Latin retundus, from Latin rotundus
Goes back to PAlb *gluna dissimilated from *g(a)nuna, which is a derivative based on IE *genu- 'knee'.
Appears to be more basic. TKD
Root /me-/, hapax legomenon inf. messi (A253 a1).
Alternatively ndohtë, both deverbal from ndoh 'make dirty', itself to dhjes 'to shit (on), ruin' < PIE **ǵʰed-i̯e- (Demiraj 1997: 290f.; LIV: 172).
From dim. of Anc.Gk. ὄνυξ > ὀνύχιον.
Middle English, from Old English nægl
appears to be most basic TKD

Onomatopoeic verb, attested once in KUB XXXIII 120 (+119 + XXXVI 31) I 26f.: man ᵈKumarbiš ŠA ᵈAnu LÚ-natar katta pašta (27) n=aš=za duškatta n=aš=za ḫa-aḫ-ḫar-aš-ta "When Kumarbi gobbled down Anu's manhood, he rejoiced and laughed." (cf. HW² Ḫ).
Denominative verb, from mend 'mind', a borrowing < Lat mentem 'id'.
An alternative lexeme 'мислити' is used in more philosophical meaning.
2. I turned my head suddenly when I heard the loud noise. An alternative lexeme is 'obratiť' but it seems to be less frequently used.
From PAlb *plata identical with IE *pleto- 'full' derived from *pel∂- 'to fill': Skt prata-, Lat com-pletus.
Msg., fsg. grande, mpl. grancj, fpl. grandis.
Msg., fsg. nere, mpl.=fpl. neris. Identical to lexeme 31656 'liver'.
Msg., fsg. frede, mpl. frêts, fpl. fredis.
Deriv. voglon. Initial /v/ is a regular process after diphtongization at the start of the word, but we expected vue-. Probably the different evolution is due to the coflict with «vueli» "oil".
Msg. bon, fsg. buine, mpl. bogns, fpl. buinisInter. = bon, adv = ben (< Lat bene), bon.
Msg., fsg. verde, mpl. verts, fpl. verdis.
Msg., fsg. lungje, mpl. luncs, fpl. lungjis.
Msg., fsg. gnove, mpl. gnûfs, gnovis.
Msg., fsg. fraide, msg. fraits, fsg. fraidis.
Msg., fsg. taronde, mpl. taronts, fpl. tarondis.
Msg., fsg. cjalde, mpl. cjalts, fpl. cjaldis.
Msg., fsg. largje, mpl. larcs, fpl. largjis.
From PIE *medʰ-i̯o-; cf. Skt. mádhya - adj. '(located in a/the) middle', subst. 'the middle'.
Denominative of կռիվ kṙiv (< CA կռիւ kṙiw) 'fight, strife; uproar'.
CA մառախուղ maṙaxowł seems already to have had the specific meaning 'fog, haze, mist; tempestuous weather', which developed from its more general meaning 'darkness, obscurity'.
Linked with the Germanic word for 'hard, steady, strong, firm, dense': OIc. fastr , OHG festi , fasti , Engl. fast , etc.
The word 'miesiąc' has today only the meaning 'month', apart from in archaic language and poetry where the meaning 'moon' is still found.
'почва, пръст' are rather professional terms like 'soil'.
2. He pushed the door to enter the house.3. Push the button to light the lamp.
Used in the construction bí + a fhios + ag, lit. "be + fear + at"
lit. 'on-growth' (i.e. that which grows on the tree), probably deverbal from 'grow'
From Old Norse fullr, from Proto-Germanic *fullaz, from Proto-Indo-European *pl̥h₁nós.
Regionally (in the East) a variant 'vaš' [vâːʃ] (or its deminutive [ˈvâʃka]) is used. They are etymologially identical (the difference is due to different phonetic development and analogy).
An alternative lexeme could be plural of 'vlas' [ˈvlâːs] 'single hair' ('vlasi' [ˈvlâːsi]). However, the normal lexeme for this meaning is collective 'kosa'.
An alternative lexeme is 'hrbat'. However, it has also a meaning 'backbone'.
An alernative lexeme could be 'miti'. However, it means 'to wash (oneself) hands and head'.
There are some alternative lexemes. 'Hititi' is regional. 'Vrgnuti/vrći' has additional meanings 'to throw strongly without specific target'.
Past stem: χʷəd-. Check pronunciation and spelling.
The lexical component "fun-ɜj" is abl. of: fun 'sleep'.
Check what happens at word boundary.
Past stem: wɜnd-. Not attested in corpus.
Past stem: (ɜ)χšad-. The initial ɜ- is prothetic.

Gloss: front of the thorax or chest, breast

Comment: Gen. ātriiehe, stem ātriia- < *ātər-(i)ya-, derived from ātər- 'fire'; Swadesh character not completly assured, since cognate of Vedic ā́sa-, Persian xāk might be missing by accident.
Acc. sg., cf. dual paršti.The stem paršta- ʿsupportʿ has to be distinguished.(Note that the stem was probably pǝršti-; the Frahang ī ōīm also gives ušaδąm “pointy back” and vaŋhąm “broad back”)
More often used as opposite to 'good' and thus probably the Swadesh term
Only in compound udarō.θrąsa-; but this may be accidental = not clearly less basic than mərəzāna- (maršū N.f is daevic)
Acc.  mazåṇtəm, neuter mazāt̰; simpler oblique stem mas- (Old Avestan maz-).
in compositum vohu.gaona- lit. "colour of the (black) blood" (Klingenschmitt 1968: 44)
nail (finger, toe), AF sruuā-, only dual and plural (also means "horn"), the Frahang ī ōīm gives also frauuāxš "horn i.e. nail"
more fequent than ā+i- (the preverb ā is not obligatory for the meaning "come")
< *azn-, suppletive to aiiarə in cases with vocalic ending
Stem kan-, later kana-(only with preverbs)
Acc. ātrəm, gen. āθrō etc.; nom. pl. ātarō
Acc. sg., dual pāδa, pāδauue; pl. paδəbiiasca
Nom. pl. m., fem. cataŋrō, stem catur-
Stem daδā-/daδ-/daθ-, OAv. dadā-/dad- (conflation with "put" in most forms)
AF zərəδaiia- (Young Avestan figurative use, zərəd is OAv.)
Acc. sg. znūm, abl.pl. žnubiias-;further attested stems: xšnu and šnu
Stem vaēδ-/vīδ-/vīθ- (OAv. vaēdā; perfect used like a present)
Gen. varəkahe (only attested in the Frahang ī ōīm F 395)
Stem juua- < *jiwa- < *jiHwa- (this would be an irregular development, cf. Hoffmann/Forssman 2004: 184: "Sonderbildung, vielleicht *-u̯a-Suffix, vgl. juua- Adj. 'lebendig'")
Synchronically suppletive comparative nazdiiah- = Vedic nédyas-
neck (ahuric), this is probably neutral because it is also used in the Frahang ī ōīm.
compound "what gives life to the tree"
Aorist suppletive darəs- (which however means rather "catch sight of")

Only once (in a word list where it is translated by "human skin"); writing 'suri' instead of 'suiri' suggests a misspelling, Klingenschmitt (1968: 46) suggests sǝuui- cf. OInd. chavī- < *sćau̯ī- (IE. *sk̑); there is also aēδa- for "skin (of the head)"
Stem asān-/ašn-; asman- normally means ʿskyʿ (no reason for long A in asān-, cf. Sanskrit ásan-)
Gen. sg. OAv. xᵛə̄ṇg, YAv. hū < *huwəŋh < *suwán-s
root given as spā(y) by Bartholomae (p.1617), cf. EWAia II p.624
Neutre θrī, fem. tišrō; gen. pl. θraiiąm

the form "uruuisiieiti" given before belongs to the root *u̯reik̑- which means "twist/turn" which is intransitive

Stem āp-/ap-, mostly plural, Nom.sg. āfš
appears to be more widely used than paθana-
stem variant razurā (f); Klingenschmitt (1968: 128) suggests for vanarǝ „tree, forest“
more frequently used than zairi- (zairi- is mostly used in compounds)
Denominal verb, based on the adjective marb 'dead'
Generally spelt with -cc in Old Irish, which would indicate /k/, but the Modern languages have /g/.
Latin alphabet: mallom (acc.sg., TB 5,15, 2),  malom (acc.sg.,TB Pocc.185,11) mallud (abl.sg. TB 20), malud (abl.sg., TB 11.)
maimas (gen.sg.f. superlative form, TB 3,7); used as an attributive adjective of carneis 'part (of the senate)'.  Cf. O. mais 'more'.

Native script: kúmbened (3.sg.pf. CA A 10), with preverb com- lexeme 28434 (= Lat. conuēnit). Latin script: cebnust (3.sg.fut., TB 20), with preverb ce-. Cf. Native Script kúmbennieís 'decision-making body of the city, assembly' (gen.sg., Po 3,4,14) a deverbal noun *kom-ben-i̯o-m from this verb *kom-ben-i̯o- 'come together' (as attested in context as kúmbened 'it came to an agreement').
Native script iúkleí (loc.sg., Cp 33.34), a dialect variant of [lexeme 28391](lex-28391)?
Latin script: zicolom (acc.sg., TB 14), zico(lom) (acc.sg., TB 15), ziculud (abl.sg., TB 16), zicel[ei] (loc.sg. TB 7), zicolom (gen.pl., TB 17).  Dialect variant of [lexeme 28390](lex-28390)?

Attested in O. púmperiais: Native script: pumperias (nom.pl., Cp 11), púmperia(s) (nom.pl., Cp 28), pumperi(as) (nom.pl., Cp 26), púmperiais (nom.pl. Cp 29, Cp 30, Cp 32), púmpe(riais) (dat. or abl. pl. Cp 27)
Attested in derived form (native script) fluusaí (dat.sg.) '(the goddess) Flora' (Po 20, TA A 24)
Native script: pettiur (Sa 17); Latin Script: petiropert (TB 15) petirupert (TB 14) as acc.pl.n. with postposition -pert.
Native script: 3.sg.perf. deded. Widely attested in both Native and Latin alphabets.
Latin script: ualaemom (nom. or acc.sg.n., TB 10). Native script: valaimas (gen.sg.f., Cp 37).
Native script: nertrak (Po 39). Used as a preposition with acc. 'left from', but in origin an abl.sg.f. *nertru- 'left', cf. Umb. nertru 'left' (adj.) [lexeme 28783](lex-28783).
Native script: numneís (gen. sg., Sa 17), num(nud) (abl. sg., Cp 32)
superlative form. Native script nessimas (nom.pl.f., Cp 24), nessimass (acc.pl.f., Cp 31), Latin script: nesimum (gen.pl.n., TB 17, 31), nesimois (abl.pl.n., TB 25).

Deities associated with Ceres through the attributive adjective kerríiúís. Usually interpreted as 'rain-deities' (Lat. dat.pl. imbribus, nom.sg. imber 'rain, heavy rain, rainstorm'. See further notes in cognate coding. Attestations: native script anafríss (dat.pl., Sa1 A9, B12)
Native script: destrst (nom. sg. f. + íst, Cp 8), a contraction of *destru íst = Lat. dext(e)ra est.
Native script: deíkum (pres.inf., Cp 36). Latin script: deicum (pres. inf., TB 10), deicans (3.pl.subj.pres., TB 9), dicust (3.sg.fut., TB 14).

Native script: staít (3.sg.pres., TA B 22), stahínt (3.pl.pres., Cp 25), stahint (3.pl.pres., Cp 25), staíet (3.pl.pres., CA B 31, Cp 24), stai[ (parsing unclear, Sa 17), staieffud (3.sg.pf.?, Cp 31), eestínt (3.pl.pres., TA B 1.3) w/ preverb ē-.
Native script: trís (nom.pl.f., Cp 24), tris (acc.pl.f., Cp 35). Latin script: t[riu]m (gen.pl., TB 32), tri]um (gen.pl., TB 29).
Native script: fangvam (acc.sg., Cm 13). Latin script: fancua (nom.pl., Cm 15).
Native script: aapam (acc.sg., Sa 10, 12), aapa[m (acc.sg., Sa 11), aapas (gen.sg. or acc.pl., Fr 2).Possibly not Swadesh term!
Native alphabet: akeneí (loc.sg., Sa1 A 18, B 23), akun. (acc.sg. or pl. Po 44); Latin alphabet: aceneis (gen.sg., TB Pocc.185,6), acenei (loc.sg., TB Pocc.185,9), acunum (gen. pl., TB 31)

Traditionally pronounced [tʰərˈtʃʰun]. Martirosyan derives թիռ- tʿiṙ- 'to fly' [lexeme 1817](lex-1817) from PIE *pter- (in turn cognate with [cognate set 700](cog-700)) and eventually *pet- 'to fly' [cognate set 1486](cog-1486), see also [cognate set 608](cog-608).
Gloss: Orig. "flying (one)"; cf. թռչիմ  [tʰərˈtʃʰim] 'I fly', ultimately from PIE *pter- 'feather'.

Comment: Cf. թիւ tʿiw 'number' from Hurrian tiw- 'speak'.

Gloss: specifically "part of day when the sun shines"

Comment: Cf. չիր čʿir 'dried fruit', formally compatible with Gk. ξηρός 'dry, parched', Skt. kṣāra- 'causitc, acrid, saline'.
Irregular aorist: կերայ ker-a-y 'I ate', traditionally pronounced [kɛɾɑ].
Probably derived from IE *sn̥gw- 'to sink, fall', cf. Goth. sigqan , OHG sinke/an , Germ. sinken , Engl. sink , etc.
Together with t'er 'side', t'er 'leaf' and t'it'eɫ/ṙn 'butterfly'< PIE *pter- 'feather; wing', probably derived from *pet- 'to fly'.

Linked with Skt. meghá- m. 'cloud, gloomy weather', Av. maēɣa- m. 'cloud', Gr. ὀμίχλη 'mist, fog', Lith. miglà 'fog', Dutch dial. miggelen 'staubregnen', etc. Other scholars consider it a loan < Iranian.
Also 'pupil (of the eye); grape, etc.'. From PIE *bud- 'to swell', same etymology as ptuk 'nipple; bud'.
Also 'abundant; perfect, whole’, adv. ‘fully, completely, firmly’.
Suppletive aorist:  հար(ե)- har(-e)- < PIE *pr̥- of 3.*per-; cf. [cognate set 600](cog-600).

Also 'circular'. Derived from PIE *bhel- 'to blow, grow, swell', cf. Gr. φαλλός m. 'penis', OIc. boli 'bull', OEngl. bula 'id.', bulluc 'young bull', Engl. bull 'id.', Lat. follis 'leather bag filled with air, ball', OIr. ball 'body part', OHG bolla f. 'Wasserblase, Fruchtbalg oder Knoten des Flachses', bilorn 'gum (in mouth)', OEngl. bealluc m. 'testicle' < *bhol-n -, OIc. bǫllr 'ball, testicle', Old Swedish bu/olde 'swelling, abscess, tumour', bu/olin 'aufgeschwollen', etc.
From PIE *k̑ō-ro-, i.e. *k̑eh₃-ro-; cf. Skt. śūla- 'dart, lance, pike, spear'; Lat. cōs ‎'whetstone' (< *k̑eh₃-ti-; catus ‎'clever, shrewd' (< *k̑h₃-to-), etc.
From reduplicated *hot-hot-. Probably derived in the preliterate period from the noun hot 'smell, odour' which is connected with Gr. ὀδμή 'smell', Lat. odor, odōris m. 'smell, scent, odour; perfume'.
Also ‘to stay, halt; to stop, rest; to wait; to appear; to dwell’. Widely considered to be cognate with cognate set 2370 'to walk, step, go'.
Identical to lexeme 28496 'to float'. Cf., byform լողիմ lołim.

More precisely: ‘to cause to fall, throw down’. Cf. Goth. sigqan. Alternative etymology: ənd and *ke-, deriving the latter from PIE *ges-, cf. OIc. kasta 'werfen' and Lat. gerere , gessī 'to carry on'.
Also 'to go/come back, return; to become'. Stem: darj.
Connected to Skt. sámā- f. 'year, season'.
mostly attested in the sense of "world", except for the Susa inscription of Darius (DSf 24) where "the earth was dug". Word sign: 𐏏.
only attested as "fear an authority", but there is no evidence that it wouldn't have been used in its broader sense
attested for time, but no evidence that it would be different for space
only attested in combination with month names, but there is no evidence to assume that 'moon' and 'month' would be different
The word 𐏃𐏁𐎫𐎫𐎹 : <hštty> is commonly read as 3pl. hištanti
Comparative form. Native alphabet: mestru (nom.sg.f. Va 24, 27, Vb 4).

Native script: avif (acc.pl., Ib 8), avef (acc.pl., Ib 10), avis (abl.pl. IIa 16) aves (abl.pl., Ia 1). Latin script: auif (acc.pl., VIb 47, 48 [two times]), aueif (acc.pl., VIa 4, 18), auuei (acc.pl., VIa 3), aueis (abl.pl., VIa 1).
Native script: atru (acc.pl.n., lb 29). Latin script: adro (acc.pl.n. VIIa 25), adrir (abl.pl.n., VIIa 9, 10, 21), adrer (abl.pl.n., VIIa 18).

Native script: menes (2.sg.fut., Ib 15), benus (2./3.sg.fut., IIb 16), benurent (3.pl.fut., Va 25, 28, Vb 5). Latin script: benust (3.sg.fut., VIb 53), benurent (3.pl.fut. VIb 57), benuso (interpetation, VIb 64, 65, VIIa 2).

Native script pir (nom./acc.sg., Ib 12 (2x), IIa 19, IIb 12, III 12, 21), pure (abl.sg. Ib 20). Latin script: pir (nom./acc.sg., Via. 20, 26, 36, 46, VIb 29, 49, 50), pureto (abl.sg. + postpos. -to, VIa20)
Native script: peři (abl.sg., Ia 29, 32). Latin script persi (abl.sg., VIb, 24, 37-39).
Attested in Latin script peturpursus 'four-footed' (dat.pl., VIb 11) < *kʷetur-pōd- 'quadriped' (cf. Gr. τετράπους, Ved. cā́tuṣpad-, Lat. quadrupēs).
Latin script: plener (abl.pl.n., VIIa 21, 34).  Possibly also Paleo-Umbrian: pleno (nom./acc.pl.n.? Um 12-15), but context unclear.

Native script: teřa (3.sg.pres.subj., Ib 34-36), titu (3.sg.imptv., Ia 33), tetu (3.sg.imptv., IIa 9, IIb 21), teřtu (3.sg.imptv., 2x in IIa 40), tertu (3.sg.imptv., IV 28), teřte 3.sg.pres.pass., Va 7), teřust (3.sg.fut., Ib 34). Latin script: dirsa (3.sg.pres.subj., Vb 13), dersa (3.sg.pres.subj., VIIa, 43, 2x in VIIa 24), dirsans (3.pl.pres.subj., Vb 11, 16), dirsas (3.sg.pres.subj., Vb 8), ditu (3.sg.imptv., VIb 10, 16, 25, VIIa 38), dirstu (3.sg.imptv., VIb 17, 38 (2x), 39, VIIa 5), dirsust (3.sg.fut., VIIa 43). Paleo-Umbrian dede (3.sg.perf., Um 11)

Palaeo-Umbrian forms; Latin script: cubrar (gen.sg.f., Um 7), Native script cupras (gen.sg.f., Um 17), cupr[as (gen.sg.f., Um 20). Cf. South Picene kuprí, qupíríh (adv.). Meaning 'good' attested by Varro (1.1.5, 159) glossing Sabine ciprum 'bonum'.
Native script: manuve (L.sg. + postpos. -en, IIb 23), mani (abl.sg., IIa 32), manf (acc.pl., IIa 38).
Native script: nertruku (abl.sg.m. + postpos. -co(m), Ia 32). Latin script: nertru (abl.sg.m., VIb 25), nertruco (abl.sg.m. + postpos. -co(m), VIb 37, 39).

Native script: numem (nom./acc.sg., Ib 17 (2x)). Latin script: nome (nom./acc.sg., 13x between VIa 30, - VIIa 47), nomner (gen.sg., VIb 54,59, VIIa 12,48), nomne (dat.sg., 40x between VIa 24 - VIa 51), nomne (abl.sg., VIa 17), nomneper (abl.sg. + postpos. -per, 40x between VIa 23 - VIIa 35).
superlative form, Latin script: nesimei (loc.sg.n., 2x in VIa 9)
Native script: rufru (acc.pl.m., Ib 24), rufra (acc.pl.f., Ib 27). Latin script: rufrer (gen.sg.m., VIa 14).

Native script: testru (abl.sg.m./n., III 23, IV 15), testruku (abl.sg.m. + postpos. -com, Ia 29), testre e (loc.sg.m. + postpos. -en, IIb 27, 28). Latin script: destram e (A.sg.f. with postpos. -en, VIb 49), destruco (abl.sg.m. with postpos. -com), destre (loc.sg.m. + postpos. -en, VIb 50), destr e (loc.sg.m. with postpos. -en, VIb 4).
Latin script: uirseto auirseto 'seen (and) unseen' (past pass.part., nom.sg., VIa 28, 38, 48, VIb 30).
Native script: kanetu (3.sg.imptv., IV 29). Latin script: procanurent (3.pl.fut. + preverb pro-, VIa 16).
Native script: zeřef (pres.part.nom.sg.m., Ia 25, 33, 34). Latin script: sersitu (3.sg.imptv., VIb 41), serse (pres.part.nom.sg.m., VIa 2, 16; VIb 17, 22, 41 (3x)).
Native script: staheren (3.pl.fut., Ib 19), Latin script: stahitu (3.sg.imptv., VIb 56), stahituto (3.pl.imptv., VIb 53), Paleo-Umbrian form: stahu (1.sg.pres., Um 10, Um 11).

Native script: vapeře (loc.sg., III 7), vapefem (acc.pl. + postpos. -en, Ib 14). Latin script: uapefe (acc.pl. + postpos. -en, VIa 10, VIb 51), uapersus (abl.pl., VIa 9), uapersusto (abl.pl. + postpos. -to, VIa 12, 13). Cf. Palaeo-Umbrian (native script) vape[řia (acc.pl.n., Um 5) < *laped-i̯o- 'made of stone'.

Native script: trif (acc.pl.m., Ib 24), tref (acc.pl.m., Ia 14, 20, Ib 1, 4), tre (acc.pl.m., Ia 1, 11), tref (acc.pl.f., Ia 7, 24, Ib 31) tre (acc.pl.f., Ib 27, 43), triia (acc.pl.n., IV 2), triiuper (acc.pl.n. + postpos. per(t), Ib 22, 22 (2x), IIb 25 (2x)), tris (abl.pl., III 18 (2x)). Latin script: trif (acc.pl.m., VIb 1,3,19,43,45, VIIa 3), treif (acc.pl.m., VIa 22), trif (acc.pl.f., VIa 50, VIb 22, VIIa 6, 41, 52), trioper (abl.pl.n. + postpos. per(t), VIIa 51).

Native script: vurtus (3.sg.fut., IIa 2), kuvertu (3.sg.imptv. + preverb ko-, Ib 9,36,38, IIa 39), kuvurtus (3.sg.fut. + preverb ko-, Ib 11). Latin script: couertu (3.sg.imptv. + preverb ko-, VIb 47, VIIa 44, 45), couortus (3.sg.fut. + preverb ko-, VIIa 39), courtust (3.sg.fut. + preverb ko-, VIa 6), couortuso (3.sg.fut.pass.? + preverb ko-, VIb 64).

Native script: tuf (acc.f.?, Ib 41), tuva (nom./acc.n., IIa 27, III 32,34), tuves (dat.m./n., III 19), tuvere (loc.abl.f. + postpos. -en, IIa 33). Latin script: dur (nom.m., VIb 50, VIIa 46), duir (dat.m./n. Vb 10, 15).
Native script: vutu (3.sg.imptv., IIa 39). Latin script anderuomu (3.sg.imptv.pass. + preverb anter, VIb 41).
Native script: alfu (acc.pl.n., Ib 29). Latin script: alfir (abl.pl.n., VIIa 25, 26), alfer (abl.pl.n., VIIa 32, 34).
Latin script: acnu (acc.sg. or pl., Vb 8, 12 14, 17).
CL ādduwa- and HL átuwa- (adj.) allow to reconstruct a PA adj. in -u̯o- which is the base of a noun *edu̯ol- 'evilness'. The latter is in turn the base of the adj. ādduwāli- (cf. Hitt. idālu-).
cf. also the extension in -azza- of CL, HL ura/i- (n.). Simplex ura- attested 1x in CL [u-r]a-an.
borrowed into Hitt. (v.) marwāi- 'to blacken'(?). Possible IE cognates: ON myrkr 'dark', mjǫrkvi 'darkness', OSax. mirki, OE mierce 'dark'.
only CL; HL áshanantisa- (n.) 'blood-offering'?, gen.adj. of *ashanant(i)- to Hitt. ashanant- 'that of blood'
assured only for CL; HL has- 'force(?)', abl.-instr. "*314"ha-sá-ti-i 'by force' KARKAMIŠ A11c §30. CL ḫāš- without final -t- (cf. Hitt. ḫaštāi-, but Lat. os).
secundary n-stem tītan from *tīta-, cf. denominative verb *tīt(a)i- 'suckle, nurse' of ptc. tītaimmi- 'nurturing', Lyc. tideimi- 'son'. Native script form ti-i-ta-ni (CL) is dat.-loc.sg.
Only HL: ha-li-i (acc.pl., BOR §11, ÇİFTLİK §17), cf. há-li-ia/iá (KARATEPE, 292); CL UD.KAM-(i)- 'day'. Hitt. attests ḫal-li-i̯a (dat.-loc.sg.) marked with the Glossenkeil.
As a finite verb only HL. CL also attests a participle ú-la-an-ti-iš (nom.sg.c.) 'dead'.
HLuv. suwani- 'dog'. CLuv. only with Sum. UR.ZÍR-(i)-.
HL BIBERE, ptc. u-wa/i-mi-i-sá.  CL ú-ut-ti-iš (2.sg.pres.)
pasūri(ya)-? cf. ACLT: inzagan-?. Semantics unclear. Cf. notes in Melchert (1993a).
ntr.; only CL. Cognate with Gk. στόμα 'mouth' (ntr.), Av. staman- 'maw' (m.). Native script form tum-ma-a-an, assumed collective plural (Melchert 1993 s.v.).
HL ta-ka-mi-i is probably a petrified form (1x, dat.-loc.) 'on the earth' (SULTANHAN § 39). Common word for 'earth' in HL is taskuira/i-. Cf. also CL tiyammi-

HL kwissa- iterative of luw. kuu̯ai̯a- (LIV² 130 n. 5a). Also attested in Hittite texts. See also luv. nahhi-, nahassa- 'fear' and hitt. naḫḫ- 'to become afraid, fear, be respectful, careful' (cf. LIV² 449). Native script form ku-wa-ya-am-ma-an-za (CL) is a participle.
only CL. The word is attested in an unclear text, but a meaning 'to light a fire' for Luv. pawariya- is ascertained. Unclear remains the lenition of the -h- in CL pāhūr.

CL pī(i̯a)-, HL piya-. CL also attests a stem pāi- (3.sg.imptv. pa-a-i-ú, pa-i-ú) whose context also suggests 'give' which would be a more archaic formation (Melchert 1993a:163). Native script form pi-i̯a-at-ta is 3.sg.pret.
Native script form is nom.-acc.sg.neut.  Also found in HL as wasu- 'good'.
CL; unclear. Hurrian loanword. Cf. also Hitt. uzuḫri-. Native script form is dat.-loc.sg.
Only CL. "May not be complete. Luvian status not assured, but supported by following tarrawaūnta." Same lexeme as YELLOW [lexeme 28855](lex-28855).
only CL. Native script form is acc.sg.
Native script form is acc.sg. Cf. nom.sg. SAG.DU-SÚ.
Native script form is 3.sg.pret. Cf. HL: AUDIRE+MI-(ma)-ti-. Denominative from tūmman(t)- 'ear'.
CL zārt-, HL zārti-. Luvian generalizes the oblique stem, see zart- and not **zir (cf. Hitt. gen.sg. kardiyas). HLuw. attests za+ra/i-za 'heart'.
Identification of lexeme as Luwian not assured, but supported by context, cf. Starke (1990:593) (StBoT 31).

HL suran-. Cognate with Hitt. karāu̯ar / karaun-. As a proper noun, CL attests the abl.-instr. with Sumerogram SI-na-ti. The genitival adjective za-ar-u̯a-ni-i̯a-ti allows a stem form *zaruu̯ar / *zarun- to be reconstructed. HL attests suran- 'horn' "CORNU+RA/I" su+ra/i-sa (nom.-acc.sg.).
(LITUUS)u-ni- 'know'; full phonetic writing (without LITUUS) by the attestation of unimis 'known' (1x, seal of Kuzi-Tešub of Karkamiš). Cf. HL uni(ya)- 'id.'.
cf. CL ipalāt(i)- 'sinisterness'. Native script form i-pa-la-a-ti is Abl.-Instr.
Precise semantics unclear. Only CL. Native script form is abl.-instr.
Gloss: body part, probably leg or thigh

Comment: Etymology unclear. Native script form is acc.sg. (Nom.sg. is only attested as Sumerogram with phonetic complement LÚ-iš).
For the reading of [ᵈE]N.ZU-aš as *Armaš 'Moon(god)' its cognacy with other Anatolian lexemes, cf. notes in cognate class.
Log. MONS. Luv. *ariyatti- also possible (cf. luw. aryattalla- 'of the mountain'). Native script form from ANCOZ 5 l.1, cf. also |MONS(-)wa/i||-ti-i-sa-wa/i-sa in KARKAMIŠ A17c 2. §2.
From *išaru-/išaru̯a- 'right-hand' with dimin. suffix -ila-? Cf. variant išaru̯ai̯(a)- from *išaru-/išaru̯a- 'right-hand' with suffix -ai̯(a)-. Cf. CL īš(ša)ra/i-, HL istra/i- 'hand'.
CL āšša- 'speak'(?) denomin. of āaš- 'mouth'; HL ásaza- is a derived iterative stem.
Cuneiform Luvian. Native script form is acc.sg. For meaning, cf. Carruba in Kratylos 7.65.
The long vowel resulting from the loss of the laryngeal did regularly 'lenite' a following dental stop:(mi-verb) m(a)nāti 'sees' < *mnéh₂-ti.

In CL proper only written with Sumerogram NIMUN, but full writing found in Hitt. u̯a-ar-u̯a-al-la-na-aš (gen.sg., preceded by Glossenkeil). The stem *u̯aru̯al- is also required by CL ᵈU̯aru̯alii̯a- 'god of sowing/fertility' (ᵈU̯a-ar-u̯a-li-i̯a-an, acc.sg.) in KBo IV 11,59.
Native script form á-sa-ta (KARATEPE 1 §31) is 3.pl.pret.act. The stem is more normally spelled with the logogram SOLIUM.
adj.; only HL and only attested logographically 3-zi; however reconstructable on basis of forms such as CL tarrii̯analli-, tarrii̯anali-; HL t(a)risu (adv.) 'three times'.
Native script form la-li-iš is Nom.sg. Also written with the Sumerogram EME.
Stem u̯ār-, -ša is just particle added to neuter singular. Native Script form u̯a-a-ar-ša is N-A Sg.
Native script form a-ru-ta (CL) is collective plural.
nom.sg. HL: ANNUS-si-sa-, CL: MU.KAM.-iš (nom.), uš-ša-a-ti (abl.).
Only CL. "May not be complete. Luvian status not assured, but supported by following tarrawaūnta." Same lexeme as GREEN [lexeme 28855](lex-28855).
HL; CL nom. sg. anim. tāwīs and coll. pl. tawa
Middle English moone, Old English mōna
Middle English ful, Old English full
Another form is qym. Borrowed < Lat cyma 'young shoots (of cabbage)'.
Goes back to PAlb *nera, further connected with Skt nár-, Gk ανηρ and ClArm ayr, all with identical meanings.

From PAlb *ksandā further compared with Skt cándati '(he) shines, is bright', candrá- 'shining; moon'. Regarding word formation, the word is also particularly close to Celt *kando-, Welsh cann 'white' and MBret cann 'full moon'.
The dust that rises from the sand.
Refers to food (meet, fruits). 'spróchniały' refers to powdery, rotting trees or wood.
Holm states this is a 'dansk form'.
Attested in many proper names, e.g. Magius, and assumed to be the general term in this meaning.
Attested in a theonym Etnosus, but assumed to contain the basic Gaulish word in this sense.
Attested in river names and other toponyms, e.g. Dubra "the waters" > Fr. Douvres.
Attested in numerous names, e.g. Cuno.
The attested form is 2 pl (imperative or indicative).
Attested in some names, e.g. Suausia ("good-eyed").
Attested in compounds and derivatives, e.g. pinpetos "fifth".
A late Gaulish form corresponding to earlier unattested *traget-.
Attested in many personal and other names, e.g. Uisulanius ("full of wisdom")
Attested form means "has given, has offered".
The Gaulish word is reported by the Roman author Pliny.
Attested in personal names, e.g. Uolto-dagae ("good-haired").
Attested in toponyms and personal names, e.g. Lama-tutus ("right-hand").
Inferred from French hydronyms, e.g. Jouanne < *yag-onia "the icy".
Attested in place names, e.g. Penne-locos ("head of the lake").
Extremely common element of personal names.
Latin bucca is often regarded as a borrowing from this Gaulish word, and the Romance words for "mouth" are descended from that Latin word.
This attested form is plural. (The expected sg. is anuan.)
Attested in derivatives, e.g. tri-noxt[ion] "(festival) of three nights".
Frequent in personal names, e.g. Seno-virus ("old man").
Attested in names, e.g. Rudianus (an epithet of Mars), Roudius.
Attested in names, e.g. the common toponym Avon.
Attested as such, and in many compound names.
Attested in toponyms, attested (e.g. Uidua) and inferred (from French toponyms), and in other names.
Attested in very many names and derivatives.
The cited form is genitive plural (the nominative singular would be bena).
This word is inferred from proper names, e.g. the toponym Rusco-ialum, and from loans into late Latin preserved in Romance.

Gloss: crust, tree bark, scab on a wound

Comment: Also 'womb, abdomen'. < PAlb *baruka, continuing *bhor-uko-, a derivative of IE *bher- 'to carry'.
fem. zezë; < Pr. Alb. *džedi, connected to MHG quāt 'dirt', OE cwéad 'bad', Lith gěda 'shame', etc.
< Pr. Alb *saka, related to Gk οπος 'juice', Lith sakaĩ 'resin', Slav *sokЪ 'juice' and other continuants of IE *sokuo- 'id'.
Note gji/gjî 'breast, chest' (mainly Gheg), according to Orel < Latin *sina <-- sinus 'curve, fold'. However a loan is doubtfully because of s- > gj- instead of expected sh-.
Goes back to Pr. Alb. *rina. Etymologically further connections to Skt rinati 'to pour'.

Late derivative of ftoh ~ ftof 'to cool, to make cold' < Pr. Alb. *wi-tāja, whose second element compares with Slav. *tajo, *tajati 'to melt', < PIE *teh₂- 'thaw, melt', here with suffix -f- < -h- < *-sk̑e-. The oppositive meaning derives from the preverb f- < *wi- < *apu- (Schumacher & Matzinger: 974).
< Pr. Alb. *dītā, connected to Germ. *tīdiz 'time' and Skt dīta 'brightness, splendour'.
< Pr. Alb. *wausi- further related to IE *ōus- 'id.'.
-zë is diminutive, but almost stable element of the word in Standard Alb.Gheg shows vo ~ ve, which according to Orel speaks for a borrowing < Latin ovum 'id'.
Also 'pair (of oxen)'. Borrowed < Lat penna, pinna 'feather'.
Also 'cloud'. Either cognate with Slav *mьgla 'darkness, mist' or borrowing from Lat nebula 'cloud'. Orel prefers the Slavic origin.
Also 'leg'. Borrowed < Rom *kamba ~ *gamba 'leg, although direction of borrowing may be uncertain.
Nor borrowed from Latin, cf. Klingenschmitt, Albanian numerals.
< Pr. Alb. *bara, related to Lat far 'sort of grain, spelt'.
This is the plural of sg. flok 'a hair'. Borrowed < Lat floccus 'lock, flock'.
Also 'bulb, berry, grain'. Borrowed < Lat coccum 'berry'.

Present indivative 3 sg., cf. also dibu preterite 3 sg. 'he/she came'. The paradigm of the verb TO COME is highly suppletive in Brittonic. The forms of the present indicative are based on PIE *h₂ag̑- in Middle and Modern Welsh, and also in Middle Cornish and Breton. In addition to this, Old and Middle Welsh possess compounds consisting of *tu- + bot 'to be' (PIE *bʰu̯eh₂-). The original meaning of these forms probably was 'to be present' (Schumacher 2004, 192, note d), Schumacher 2011, 186). Evans (1964, 133) lists MW dybyd etc. as "consuetudinal present and future", MW dybu as "preterite 2". This additional notion could be present in the OW forms as well. In view of Middle Welsh, the existence of forms based on Proto-Celtic *ag- seems probable. These forms most likely conveyed the basic meaning of COMING, without any additional notions. They are not attested in Old Welsh, however, due to the fragmentary nature of the corpus.

'Planina' is more frequent and neutral than 'gora'.. There are some alternative lexemes. 'Brijeg' and 'brežuljak' can be excluded rather without doubs, as they refer to small hills. 'Brdo' [br̩̂dɔ] is bigger, up to ca. 500 meters of relative height but it is still more a 'hill' than a 'mountian'. 'Planina' is described as everything over ca. 500 meters of relative height (usually with more than one top) and 'gora' is a synonyme of 'planina', normally refering to a 'planina' of an average height.

Also 'right' and 'true'. There are three synonyms which can occur at parallel places in different texts (e.g. translation of the Bible). There are two alternative lexemes: 'opuchnúti' and 'odúti (sě)'. The lexeme 'otéci' is attested in many various contexts (whole body, tongue, womb, limb,  wound, leg, neck, belly, lips, gums, cheeks, breast) and is likely to be most generic. 'odúti (sě)' refers to 'leg, arm, belly' and probably denotes a great swelling. 'opuchnúti' refers in most cases to 'eyes, lips, face' only sometimes to 'knee, arm'.
Possible alternative lexemes are 'ledvie' and 'bedro'. However, it seems that 'thigh' is not their main meaning.

The lexeme 'hoditi' has normally the meanign 'fit, suit' in . There is also a secondary meaning 'hit, hit something by throwing' but this lexeme is not the Swadesh term in Old Czech yet. 'kydnúti, kydati' is less frequented and occurs in the context of 'dung, mud, dirt'. 'metati' is typically imperfective.

As Slavic languages do not differ (at least as to the root, not alwas as to the whole word) between swimming (of living beings) and floating (of things) it can be assumed that the proper Swadesh term contained the same root as.
The context is 'six winged angels', the author of the manuscript ordered an icon. The word comes most probably from the educated language and not from the dialect itself.

In Bernese German (as well as other German varieties), there are two possible translations for the English verb to hit: (i) 'schlah' /ʃlaː/, which primarily profiles the activity of wielding an instrument with the purpose of hitting somebody or something, and (ii) 'träffe' /træffə/, which primarily profiles the accomplishment of establishing physical contact between the instrument and the hit entity. I assume that you are looking for the first concept.

Std.Alb. kufizë 'term' (in mathematics), from kufizon '(de)limit, mark/share a border' is likely not connected. On semantic grounds (denoting rather the hollow than the navel itself) better treated as a diminutive of gufë 'cave; hollow (esp. in a trunk tree)' [also: 'sth. puffed up; effusion, surge, swell'] and/or Arb. gufër 'mouth of a volcano, crater' (Newmark, Oxford Dict.). Anlaut mutation due to analogy with (Std.)Alb. kërthizë 'navel'?Alb. gufë, in turn, must be connected with (prefixed) zgavër (~ zguer) 'hole', cf. zgurdhë 'rectum' (according to Orel and Demiraj s.v. dervied from the latter).< PIE *gerbʰ 'to carve, notch' or *gʰrebʰ 'to dig' (+prefix *eks-)?
Note the semantic specialization and unclear lowering of the vowel compared to Std.Alb. ndej. Eventually contamination with ndan 'to seperate'.

Extended root PIE *h₁ei̯-k-/h₁i-k-, eventually of the type "facere".Likely also attested in the prefixed variant shkoj 'go, walk' and the unextended root *h₁ei̯- in heavily reshaped vete 'go'.Since both, the unextended as well as the extended root variant survive, a split might have occurred in different positions of the paradigm like the -k- evolving in the aorist or imperative.

Loan from Calab. ad(d)urare, -ari 'to smell' with apheresis. Cf. Std.-Ital. odorare; < Lat. odōrāre.

Common Alb. uses verdhë to denote 'yellow', itself < (Vul)Lat. viridem 'green' or Ital. verde 'green' (thus Demiraj 105).Here, virdhe is either a re-loan from Italian (the vocalism could speak in favor of this with Italian closed /e/ --> /i/) or influenced by it.

Connection with vb. Std.Alb, mbështét/s 'to stand, prop, lean, lay down' (Arbëresh also 'defend'); refl. The form dẅē is more common in list-counting, and a shorter form dwı (with non-fronted w) is more common with a following noun.

The term dıḷ refers to the upper part of the belly, and also to the internal organs, especially the stomach. The word zıg refers to the belly and the abdomen.
Some speakers of this variety use the form nawk, but  the interviewed speaker uses nāwk.

Both qwıl and pā are used commonly (by the speaker and in the language community generally) for the meaning ‘foot/leg’. The term pā, which comes from Persian, is dominant in formal contexts, and is most common among urban, educated, and younger speakers of the language.

The term zānü, which is similar to Persian zānu, is also used other speakers of this variety, but is not often used by the interviewed speaker. The words kaškıḷa and zırānü are both common and have the exact same meaning. The word kaškıḷa is cognate for the word 'kneecap' in other Iranic varieties, for example Bakhtiari kaškak.

Both qwıl and pā are used commonly (by the speaker and in the language community generally) for the meaning ‘foot/leg’. The term pā, which comes from Persian, is dominant in formal contexts, and is most common among urban, educated, and younger speakers of the language.

The term qaḷb, which is borrowed from Arabic via Persian, is a more strictly anatomical for ‘heart’. The older term dıḷ also refers to this organ, but has a broader semantic range and also includes the inside of the thorax and upper abdomen generally, and is also used figuratively as the seat of emotion.
Some speakers of this variety, but not the interviewed speaker, use the form pyāg.

The word tūz is a general term for dust, including dust in the air. The term gart is reserved for a 'dusting', i.e., a layer of dust on a surface.

The synonymous terms hawz and gwıḷam both refer to small, seasonal lakes, which are the only type of lake in the region. The term daryāča has been recently borrowed from Persian, but corresponds more closely to the CoBL meaning of ‘lake’, so it is given here.
Final syllable with the vowel ı is stressed here, cf. ‘snow’ where it is unstressed.

The word māḷ is commonly used, but its meaning extends to a residence generally, and can also be used for tents where nomads live. The word xānıg necessarily refers to a house constructed with hard materials.
This word is two syllables in the speaker’s variety, with no clear glide between the vowels. Some other speakers pronounce it as a single syllable: qaẅn.

Both terms (čarmıg, sıfēd) are commonly used. The term sıfēd (which resembles Southwestern Iranic spēd/sefid) is more common in formal contexts, and among educated and younger speakers.

The forms given here are simple past, not progressive past (which would add dāšt, and sometimes a dı- prefix, before the verb). The present form of this verb (and many other vowel-final present verbs) can also end in a postvocalic g.

The forms given here are simple present, not progressive present (which would add dērē, and sometimes a dı- prefix, before the verb). The final vowels in all such forms are unstressed and non-syllabic. The initial d- is found in the basic present form for this verb (cf. its use on other verbs to mark progressive aspect explicitly). A form yāē is attested in other varieties, however. The present form of this verb (and many other vowel-final present verbs) can also end in a postvocalic g.
The form xıṛē dā, where the object is explicitly mentioned, is more typical; however, we give the bare form here.

Attested in the Catholicon (1499), equivalent of Middle French riuyere, fleuve and Latin rivus. The latter denotes both brooks and streamlet and big rivers leading to the sea (cf. German Strom). The Latin examples translated into French all mention bigger rivers, cf. hic geon 'cest le fleue de paradis terrestre', hic padus 'ung fleuue' (Po), hic remis 'la riuiere de rin' (Rhine), hoc rodanū 'la riuiere de rosne' (Rhône).Quiquer's dictionary 'Nomenclator' (1633) only gives riffier 'river', none of the other Breton words.

The Catholicon does not mention OBr. staer, ModBr. stêr, which is used in Leoneg and the Literary Standard. Quiquer's dirctionary 'Nomenclator' (1633) has both riffier 'fleuve, rivière' and gouaz-dour 'un ruisseau', bot none of the other terms. Maunoir's dictionary from 1659 gives riuier and ster for French rivière in addition to ster in the meaning of lavoir.

Although also the name of the internal organ 'stomach', in the variety of English targeted here, i.e. standard British English and following majority usage in England, the word 'stomach' has broadened to refer to the abdomen in general, and is has become the default, unmarked word for the target sense here.  The lexeme 'belly' is more marked in register, often with overtones of a protruding 'pot belly'..

This may strike speakers of many varieties of English as unusual, but needs to be seen in the context of significant differences between different varieties of English worldwide.  Highly relevant is that in the variety of English targeted here, i.e. standard British English and following majority usage in England, the lexemes 'ill' and 'unwell' are very widely used, where other varieties use 'sick'.  This allows a particular usage of '(being) sick', in the specific sense of vomiting, especially in the most common aspectual and tense uses.  So in this specific variety, in the default, unmarked register, speakers most often use formulations like "S/he has been sick" to mean not "S/he has been ill" (as they would normally refer to a period of ill health), but to mean specifically "S/he has (just) vomited":  Likewise, normal usage would be: "Please stop the car, I’m going to be sick.", meaning specifically that the speaker felt s/he was about to vomit.The lexeme 'vomit' in this variety has rather narrower register uses, slightly elevated ad 'medical'.  There are also a host of other familiar register lexemes, as in other varieties of English.
